Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.09,0:00:05.28,Default,,0,0,0,,In his 1971 book, {\i1}The Descent of Man{\i0}, Charles Darwin suggested
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.28,0:00:09.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that humans were descended from ancestral African apes
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.66,0:00:15.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now since then, many fossils of ancestral human-like species have been discovered
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.58,0:00:17.80,Default,,0,0,0,,We have about twenty of these species now
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.08,0:00:20.62,Default,,0,0,0,,and all of these "hominins", as we call them
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.62,0:00:23.06,Default,,0,0,0,,are more closely related to us humans
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.06,0:00:27.27,Default,,0,0,0,,than they are to African apes like chimpanzees and gorillas.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.37,0:00:31.93,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the most famous Hominin species is {\i1}Australopithecus aforensis{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.93,0:00:36.34,Default,,0,0,0,,and one of the most famous fossils of that species is called "Lucy"
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.34,0:00:40.56,Default,,0,0,0,,and she was discovered in 1974 in Ethiopia
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.18,0:00:45.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And in fact there was much more of Lucy's skeleton than I've got represented here
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.48,0:00:48.35,Default,,0,0,0,,We have about 40% of her skeleton
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.35,0:00:51.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and that's enough to see that there are important differences
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.58,0:00:53.98,Default,,0,0,0,,between her skeleton and that of
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.98,0:00:56.81,Default,,0,0,0,,living African apes like chimpanzees and gorillas
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.17,0:01:00.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and those differences relate to the way in which she moved around.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.85,0:01:03.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We know from looking at her skeleton
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.29,0:01:07.58,Default,,0,0,0,,that Lucy was adapted to walking upright on two legs.
